Disk Forensics > [T4]: Tracking User Activity and Account Events

(2) Security.evtx

Windows stores Login/Logout events' details in Security.evtx event log file and tracks it in multiple event IDs based on their type. These events are:

  1. Event ID 4624: Successful logon event.
  2. Event ID 4625: Failed logon event.
  3. Event ID 4634: Account Logoff or, better said, session terminated irrespective of whether the user logged off or not. For example, closing an RDP session by clicking on X to close the RDP window without signing out first.
  4. Event ID 4647: User Initiated Logoff. This event is generated when a user manually logs off. For example, logging off from the start menu -> Profile picture -> signout. All 4647 events must have a corresponding 4634 because every log-off will terminate the session. But not all 4634 will have a relevant 4647 because a session could be terminated without logging off.
  5. Event ID 4672 special privileges assigned to new logon: This event is generated whenever an account with administrative privileges logs on. It will also be generated for any service account with admin rights.
  6. Event ID 4648 - A logon was attempted using explicit credentials. This event is generated when an account logs in using a different privilege and has to explicitly enter credentials, such as the RUNAS command. Another example is when User Account Control (UAC) prompts a non-admin user to enter credentials for an account with administrative rights.

4624 event - (zoom in)

  1. Event ID 4624 log entry.
  2. The 'Subject' section identifies the account/service that requested the logon - NOT the user who just logged on. It is usually blank or service and not user-related information.
  3. The 'Logon Type' shows how the user logged into the system. In this event, Logon type 3 indicates a network login. Refer to this list for all available login types.
  4. Security ID: contains the account's SID.
  5. Account name: account's username.
  6. Login ID: a unique identifier for each login session. This value is used to correlate between login and logout events. In other words, there should be one other logout event 4634, with the same Login ID.
  7. The 'Network Information' section contains information about the source IP address. The system where this login session originated from.

 

Let's have a look at a logout event.

4634 log-off event - (zoom in)

  1. Event ID 4634 log entry.
  2. Login ID: as indicated in event 4624 above, this field is used to correlate between login/logout events. In this example, the Login ID in both figures is 0x24f79b.

Another two important events to track are account creation (4720) and account deletion (4726) logs.

 

Account creation 4720 event - (zoom in)

  1. Account creation event ID 4720 log entry.
  2. The 'subject' section contains information about the account that created the new account.
  3. Account SID.
  4. Account Name.
  5. UAC policies are assigned to the created account.
